Being able to defend yourself eases your mind so you can live a happier life. You can invest 20 years into a job but outside of that job, you have nothing to show for. When you practice martial arts, you bring it around with you wherever you go. Greater range of motion is a big self-confidence booster. You feel like you're worth something, and can approach that girl, or that boss. You feel like you're worth something before even learning the first thing about whatever career you decide to pursue. You can teach others how to defend themselves too. It's a party trick you can bring anywhere to get the good kind of attention. Chicks dig a man that can protect her. I enjoy anything creative I can do to express myself. That's drawing, improvising on the piano, singing, programming, writing, sports, yoga, tai chi, etc. For me, even just the exercise aspect makes martial arts worthwhile to me. But there is an aspect of perfection to martial arts which appeals to me, being a perfectionist and all. Any way I can strive for perfection, especially using the body alone, I find very attractive. It's like eating healthy, no matter where you go in life at least you'd be healthy. It's the same with martial arts, no matter where you go in life, at least you'll feel more confident in a bad situation. You don't have to get physical, but if you believe in yourself, being able to defend yourself can have a great impact on your self-confidence in intimidating situations. It's that self-confidence, more than anything, which I feel is the most worthwhile. That or the meditative, internal aspect. Being able to meditate can really calm the mind and make you a happier person.

Love is something two-way. Unless both people are happy, it is doomed to failure. Knowing when to throw in the towel takes experience and is a sign of maturity as it saves you both time. The more crap you put up with, the more you'll get crapped on. There's certain things a relationship needs to be healthy. If it's one-sided giving, then one person is using the other. Even if one person has an "endless" supply to give, it's an unhealthy relationship. Even in the midst of an infinite flow of giving, the other person won't feel they're giving anything in return and might leave because it's not helping them grow. If you have your eye on someone else, it's also a sign you're not working out with the person you're breaking up with. If you're unable to compliment them, perhaps you don't see anything in them at all. It takes courage to initiate a break up, you should be proud. If you're giving yourself a hard time *how* you broke up, don't worry about it. Just think about how many dudes she's been with before you and how many she'll be with after you. There's no reason to be hard on yourself. "We could have been together longer if only I..." Even if both parties love each other and put in loads of effort, some people live such completely different life styles, that no amount of effort can seal the gap. Things like religion, beliefs, health, these are things which can be hard to seal the gap. If you feel bad about breaking up, you can make you intentions for breaking up clear so they don't hate you. Nobody likes being hated. It's nice to have an extra friend if you need one, but just make it clear it's best if you go separate ways. But if you try to break up in a nice way, remaining "just friends", prepare to get emailed and texted later in life. Whether you want to remain friends or not, both have their pros and cons.

The problem with your argument is the assumption that a computer doesn't know or understand while we do. They've done experiments which show electric signals sent to the brain can cause a limb to move. Why can't brain surgery advance to the point they can upload 20 years of education? Does an unconscious or dead person have "knowledge"? Why can't we argue a computer isn't functioning "properly" until it passes the turing test under the same pretext an unconscious human can't lie? Do computers feel pain? (no) What about a "properly" functioning computer? We can program it to act like it does. Do humans feel pain? There's people out there with [congenital analgesia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congenital_insensitivity_to_pain) which can't. So a properly functioning human does, maybe a properly functioning computer does too. Losing a limb can suck, but can't a robot also lose a limb and feel the "pain" of trying to function normally? Ah, but a robot you can just repair the lost limb. Yet with humans, stem cell research is nearly at the stage we can replace limbs. No matter how you look at it, we're just a program. A person can be hypnotized and thus reprogrammed to a certain extent. Imagine someone with amnesia so severe, they forgot how to speak, how to make sense of their vision, and even how to breathe. They get hooked up to some machine to help them breathe until their brain heals enough for them to remember how to breathe. Then they relearn how to make sense of 3-dimensional shapes, etc.
So why can't a computer/robot just be programmed to have reasons to lie in certain situations which it "knows" is false?
